# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-i-of-russia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The **first cholera pandemic** (1817–1824), also known as the **first Asiatic cholera pandemic** or **Asiatic cholera**, began near the city of Calcutta and spread throughout South Asia and Southeast Asia to the Middle East, Eastern Africa and the Mediterranean coast.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] While cholera had spread across India many times previously, this outbreak went further; it reached as far as China and the Mediterranean Sea before subsiding.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Millions of people died as a result of this pandemic, including approximately 10,000 troops in British service, which attracted European attention.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] This was the first of several cholera pandemics to sweep through Asia and Europe during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] This first pandemic spread over an unprecedented range of territory, affecting almost every country in Asia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The name cholera had been used in previous centuries to describe illnesses involving nausea and vomiting.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Today, cholera specifically describes illness caused by the *Vibrio cholerae* bacteria.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] There are numerous examples of epidemics prior to 1817 which are suspected as being cholera.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the sixth century BCE cholera-like symptoms were described by an Indian text.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Indeed, descriptions of a disease in India from as far back as 2,500 years ago describe an illness reminiscent of cholera.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Greek physician Hippocrates wrote about an illness resembling cholera about 2,400 years ago, as did Roman physician Galen roughly 500 years later in the 2nd century.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the 16th century, an outbreak of acute diarrhea was reported to have occurred in the East Indies by the Dutch.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] A similar outbreak was recorded in 1669 in China.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] But, there is no evidence of "true Asiatic Cholera" prior to 1781, in which the first well-documented epidemic occurred.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Having begun in southern India, it would later spread to eastern India and eventually Sri Lanka.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Cholera was endemic to the lower Ganges River.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] At festival times, pilgrims frequently contracted the disease there and carried it back to other parts of India on their returns, where it would spread, then subside.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The first cholera pandemic started similarly, as an outbreak that was suspected to have begun in 1817 in the town of Jessore.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Some epidemiologists and medical historians have suggested that it spread globally through a Hindu pilgrimage, the Kumbh Mela*,* on the upper Ganges River.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Earlier outbreaks of cholera had occurred near Purnia in Bihar, but scholars think these were independent events.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In 1817, cholera began spreading outside the Ganges Delta.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] By September 1817, the disease had reached Calcutta on the Bay of Bengal and quickly spread to the rest of the subcontinent.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] By 1818 the disease broke out in Bombay, on the west coast.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] After spreading beyond India, the first cholera pandemic hit other parts of Asia and the African coast the hardest.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] It would not be until later epidemics of cholera that it would ravage Europe and the Americas.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] When the epidemic reached Russia and specifically Astrakhan, their response was to formulate an anti-Cholera program in 1823.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] This program was headed by a German physician by the name of Dr.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The Anti-Cholera program inspired the creation of a medical-administration board by Tsar Alexander I that inspired similar medical administration across Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In 1824, transmission of the disease ended.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Some researchers believe that may have been due to the cold winter of 1823–1824, which would have killed the bacteria in the water supplies.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The spread of the first cholera pandemic was closely linked to warfare and trade.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] According to economic history professor Donato Gómez-Diaz, "[advances] in commercial exchange and navigation contributed to cholera’s dispersion." Navy and merchant ships carried people with the disease to the shores of the Indian Ocean, from Africa to Indonesia, and north to China and Japan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] During the Ottoman-Persian War of 1821–1823, cholera would affect both armies in what is modern-day Armenia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Hindu pilgrims spread cholera within the subcontinent, as had happened many times previously, and British forces carried it overland to Nepal and Afghanistan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In 1821, a British military force carried cholera to Oman after becoming infected with it in India.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The total deaths from the epidemic remain unknown.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Scholars of particular areas have estimated death tolls.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] For instance, some estimate that Bangkok might have suffered 30,000 deaths from the disease.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In Semarang, Central Java, 1,225 people died in eleven days in April 1821.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In total, over 100,000 people died as a result of cholera on Java during the first pandemic.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Also in 1821, Basra, Iraq saw 18,000 deaths in less than a month's time.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the same year, it is estimated that up to 100,000 deaths occurred in Korea.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Vietnamese royal archives recorded 206,835 people died from the disease.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the southwest of the Mekong Delta, the outbreak swept through the constructing Vĩnh Tế Canal, killing thousand of workers (most of them Cambodians) and triggered a Cambodian uprising in later that year.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The well-known novelist Nguyễn Du died contracting the disease.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] During the Ottoman–Persian War of 1821–1823, cholera and plague outbreaks also ravaged Qajar Iran.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Contemporary Persian sources report that around 100,000 people died due to these diseases in the region.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Ottoman historian Cevdet Pasha noted that the cholera epidemic severely impacted the Iranian army, forcing Abbas Mirza’s troops into retreat and leaving many soldiers unburied.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] According to Cevdet, the epidemic was one of the decisive reasons for Iran's decision to end the war and make peace with the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] As for India, the initially reported mortality rate was estimated to be 1.25 million per year, placing the death toll at around 8,750,000.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] According to historian Samuel Kohn, in antiquity, epidemics frequently brought members of a society together.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] However, some diseases such as cholera produced the opposite result, triggering blame and even violence against those people who were perceived as being from regions in which people were believed to be infected with the disease.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Oftentimes, fear of cholera outbreaks would lead to increased racial tensions.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The cholera pandemic's origin in India led to a rise in anti-Asian sentiment, especially towards Indian people and culture, in the West during the initial outbreak and following more outbreaks decades later.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The disease was subsequently associated with Asia and South Asia, in particular, was seen as in some way to blame for cholera.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Derision towards Indian cultural practices, especially Hindu pilgrimages, and hygiene following the initial outbreak were reported.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Medical professionals of the time were also noted for relying on moral judgments and generalizations of Indian people on pilgrimages.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The sanitary commissioner of Bengal, David Smith, wrote that "the human mind can scarcely sink lower than it has done in connection with the appalling degeneration of idol-worship at Pooree".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] During the outbreak, the colonial authorities launched inquiries into the medical conditions of South Asian people on pilgrimages and eventually classified pilgrims as a "dangerous class" due their belief that many pilgrims were infected with cholera, placing them under surveillance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the years after the pandemic subsided in many areas of the world, there were still small outbreaks, and pockets of cholera remained.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] In the period from 1823 to 1829, the first cholera outbreak remained outside of much of Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Its spread into Europe in the years after the initial outbreak started with the spread of the bacterium to the Russian empire yet again.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Historians theorize that the spread back into Europe was largely due to its movement in the Russian river system and with passengers on the river.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] This movement of the virus in the rivers of Russia allowed cholera to reach England by 1832, and the Americas shortly afterward.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The bacterium also was theorized to have spread into England from British soldiers returning home after tours of duty in India, many of them serving in the Bombay Army which was stationed where the pandemic broke out.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Special deputations from the west traveled to Russia to observe the Russian response and formulate a plan to deal with these pocketed outbreaks.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Reports from this committee of scientists were bleak, with a Dr.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Rauch proclaiming that, "the cholera will not be cured by nature's powers alone without the help of art...".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] Rauch's findings was that no one standardized method was the key to controlling an outbreak.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] By 1835, these pockets of the bacterium claimed hundreds of thousands of lives.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] This timeline from 1826 to 1837 is widely described as the second cholera pandemic.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/1817-1824-cholera-pandemic] The last of the seven main cholera pandemics in history extends into the modern day.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Aargau is one of the most northerly cantons of Switzerland, and contains the lower course of the Aare River from which the name *Aar-gau* ("Aare province") is drawn.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It is one of the most densely populated regions of Switzerland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The area of Aargau and the surrounding areas were controlled by the Helvetians, a tribe of Celts, as far back as 200 BC.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It was eventually occupied by the Romans and then by the 6th century, the Franks.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Romans built a major settlement called Vindonissa, near the present location of Brugg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The reconstructed Old High German name of Aargau is *Argowe*, first unambiguously attested (in the spelling *Argue*) in 795.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Within the Frankish Empire (8th to 10th centuries), the area was a disputed border region between the duchies of Alamannia and Burgundy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] A line of the von Wetterau (Conradines) intermittently held the countship of Aargau from 750 until about 1030, when they lost it (having in the meantime taken the name von Tegerfelden).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] This division became the ill-defined (and sparsely settled) outer border of the early Holy Roman Empire at its formation in the second half of the 10th century.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Most of the region came under the control of the ducal house of Zähringen and the comital houses of Habsburg and Kyburg by about 1200.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the second half of the 13th century, the territory became divided between the territories claimed by the imperial cities of Bern, Lucerne and Solothurn and the Swiss canton of Unterwalden.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The remaining portion, largely corresponding to the modern canton of Aargau, remained under the control of the Habsburgs until the "conquest of Aargau" by the Old Swiss Confederacy in 1415.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Habsburg Castle itself, the original seat of the House of Habsburg, was taken by Bern in April 1415.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Habsburgs had founded a number of monasteries (with some structures enduring, e.g., in Wettingen and Muri), the closing of which by the government in 1841 was a contributing factor to the outbreak of the Swiss civil war – the "Sonderbund War" – in 1847.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] When Frederick IV of Habsburg sided with Antipope John XXIII at the Council of Constance, Emperor Sigismund placed him under the Imperial ban.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In July 1414, the Pope visited Bern and received assurances from the that they would move against the Habsburgs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] A few months later the Swiss Confederation denounced the Treaty of 1412.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Shortly thereafter in 1415, Bern and the rest of the Swiss Confederation used the ban as a pretext to invade the Aargau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Confederation was able to quickly conquer the towns of Aarau, Lenzburg, Brugg and Zofingen along with most of the Habsburg castles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Bern kept the southwest portion (Zofingen, Aarburg, Aarau, Lenzburg, and Brugg), northward to the confluence of the Aare and Reuss.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The important city of Baden was taken by a united Swiss army and governed by all 8 members of the Confederation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Some districts, named the *Freie Ämter* (*free bailiwicks*) – Mellingen, Muri, Villmergen, and Bremgarten, with the countship of Baden – were governed as "subject lands" by all or some of the Confederates.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Shortly after the conquest of the Aargau by the Swiss, Frederick humbled himself to the Pope.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Pope reconciled with him and ordered all of the taken lands to be returned.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Swiss refused and years later after no serious attempts at re-acquisition, the Duke officially relinquished rights to the Swiss.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Bern's portion of the Aargau came to be known as the Unteraargau, also referred to as the Berner or Bernese Aargau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 1514 Bern expanded north into the Jura and so came into possession of several strategically important mountain passes into the Austrian Fricktal.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] This land was added to the Unteraargau and was directly ruled from Bern.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It was divided into seven rural bailiwicks and four administrative cities, Aarau, Zofingen, Lenzburg and Brugg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] While the Habsburgs were driven out, many of their minor nobles were allowed to keep their lands and offices, though over time they lost power to the Bernese government.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The bailiwick administration was based on a very small staff of officials, mostly made up of Bernese citizens, but with a few locals.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] When Bern converted during the Protestant Reformation in 1528, the Unteraargau also converted.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] At the beginning of the 16th century a number of Anabaptists migrated into the upper Wynen and Rueder valleys from Zurich.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Despite pressure from the Bernese authorities in the 16th and 17th centuries, Anabaptism never entirely disappeared from the Unteraargau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Bern used the Aargau bailiwicks mostly as a source of grain for the rest of the city-state.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The administrative cities remained economically only of regional importance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] However, in the 17th and 18th centuries Bern encouraged industrial development in Unteraargau and by the late 18th century it was the most industrialized region in the city-state.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The high industrialization led to high population growth in the 18th century, for example between 1764 and 1798, the population grew by 35%, far more than in other parts of the canton.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 1870 the proportion of farmers in Aarau, Lenzburg, Kulm, and Zofingen districts was 34–40%, while in the other districts it was 46–57%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The rest of the Freie Ämter were collectively administered as subject territories by the rest of the Confederation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Muri *Amt* was assigned to Zürich, Lucerne, Schwyz, Unterwalden, Zug and Glarus, while the *Ämter* of Meienberg, Richensee and Villmergen were first given to Lucerne alone.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The final boundary was set in 1425 by an arbitration tribunal and Lucerne had to give the three *Ämter* to be collectively ruled.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The four *Ämter* were then consolidated under a single Confederation bailiff into what was known in the 15th century as the *Waggental* Bailiwick (German: *Vogtei im Waggental*).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the 16th century, it came to be known as the *Vogtei der Freien Ämter*.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] While the *Freien Ämter* often had independent lower courts, they were forced to accept the Confederation's sovereignty.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Finally, in 1532, the canton of Uri became part of the collective administration of the Freien Ämter.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] At the time of the Protestant Reformation, the majority of the Ämter converted to the new faith.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 1529, a wave of iconoclasm swept through the area and wiped away much of the old religion.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] After the defeat of Zürich in the second Battle of Kappel in 1531, the victorious five Catholic cantons marched their troops into the Freie Ämter and reconverted them to Catholicism.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the First War of Villmergen, in 1656, and the Toggenburg War (or Second War of Villmergen), in 1712, the Freie Ämter became the staging ground for the warring Reformed and Catholic armies.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] While the peace after the 1656 war did not change the status quo, the fourth Peace of Aarau in 1712 brought about a reorganization of power relations.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The victory gave Zürich the opportunity to force the Catholic cantons out of the government in the county of Baden and the adjacent area of the Freie Ämter.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Freie Ämter were then divided in two by a line drawn from the gallows in Fahrwangen to the Oberlunkhofen church steeple.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The northern part, the so-called Unteren Freie Ämter (lower Freie Ämter), which included the districts of Boswil (in part) and Hermetschwil and the Niederamt, were ruled by Zürich, Bern and Glarus.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The southern part, the Oberen Freie Ämter (upper Freie Ämter), were ruled by the previous seven cantons but Bern was added to make an eighth.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] During the Helvetic Republic (1798–1803), the county of Baden, the Freie Ämter and the area known as the Kelleramt were combined into the canton of Baden.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The County of Baden was a shared condominium of the entire Old Swiss Confederacy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] After the Confederacy conquest in 1415, they retained much of the Habsburg legal structure, which caused a number of problems.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The local nobility had the right to hold the low court in only about one fifth of the territory.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were over 30 different nobles who had the right to hold courts scattered around the surrounding lands.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] All these overlapping jurisdictions caused numerous conflicts, but gradually the Confederation was able to acquire these rights in the county.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The cities of Baden, Bremgarten and Mellingen became the administrative centers and held the high courts.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Together with the courts, the three administrative centers had considerable local autonomy, but were ruled by a governor who was appointed by the *Acht Orte* every two years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] After the Protestant victory at the Second Battle of Villmergen, the administration of the County changed slightly.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Instead of the *Acht Orte* appointing a bailiff together, Zürich and Bern each appointed the governor for 7 out of 16 years while Glarus appointed him for the remaining two years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The chaotic legal structure and fragmented land ownership combined with a tradition of dividing the land among all the heirs in an inheritance prevented any large scale reforms.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The governor tried in the 18th century to reform and standardize laws and ownership across the county, but with limited success.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] With an ever-changing administration, the County lacked a coherent long-term economic policy or support for reforms.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] By the end of the 18th century there were no factories or mills and only a few small cottage industries along the border with Zürich.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Road construction first became a priority after 1750, when Zürich and Bern began appointing a governor for seven years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] During the Protestant Reformation, some of the municipalities converted to the new faith.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] However, starting in 1531, some of the old parishes were converted back to the old faith.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The governors were appointed from both Catholic and Protestant cantons and since they changed every two years, neither faith gained a majority in the county.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] After the French invasion, on 19 March 1798, the governments of Zürich and Bern agreed to the creation of the short lived canton of Baden in the Helvetic Republic.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] With the Act of Mediation in 1803, the canton of Baden was dissolved.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Portions of the lands of the former County of Baden now became the District of Baden in the newly created canton of Aargau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] After World War II, this formerly agrarian region saw striking growth and became the district with the largest and densest population in the canton (110,000 in 1990, 715 persons per km2).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The contemporary canton of Aargau was formed in 1803, a canton of the Swiss Confederation as a result of the Act of Mediation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It was a combination of three short-lived cantons of the Helvetic Republic: Aargau (1798–1803), Baden (1798–1803) and Fricktal (1802–1803).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Its creation is therefore rooted in the Napoleonic era.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the year 2003, the canton of Aargau celebrated its 200th anniversary.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] French forces occupied the Aargau from 10 March to 18 April 1798; thereafter the Bernese portion became the canton of Aargau and the remainder formed the canton of Baden.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Aborted plans to merge the two halves came in 1801 and 1802, and they were eventually united under the name Aargau, which was then admitted as a full member of the reconstituted Confederation following the Act of Mediation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Some parts of the canton of Baden at this point were transferred to other cantons: the *Amt* of Hitzkirch to Lucerne, whilst Hüttikon, Oetwil an der Limmat, Dietikon and Schlieren went to Zürich.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In return, Lucerne's *Amt* of Merenschwand was transferred to Aargau (district of Muri).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the 17th century, Aargau was the only federal condominium where Jews were tolerated.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 1774, they were restricted to just two towns, Endingen and Lengnau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] While the rural upper class pressed incessantly for the expulsion of the Jews, the financial interests of the authorities prevented it.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] They imposed special taxes on peddling and cattle trading, the primary Jewish professions.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Protestant occupiers also enjoyed the discomfort of the local Catholics by the presence of the Jewish community.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Jews were directly subordinate to the governor; from 1696, they were compelled to renew a letter of protection from him every 16 years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] During this period, Jews and Christians were not allowed to live under the same roof, neither were Jews allowed to own land or houses.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] They were taxed at a much higher rate than others and, in 1712, the Lengnau community was "pillaged." In 1760, they were further restricted regarding marriages and procreation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] An exorbitant tax was levied on marriage licenses; oftentimes, they were outright refused.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] This remained the case until the 19th century.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 1799, the Helvetic republic abolished all special tolls, and, in 1802, removed the poll tax.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] On 5 May 1809, they were declared citizens and given broad rights regarding trade and farming.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] They were still restricted to Endingen and Lengnau until 7 May 1846, when their right to move and reside freely within the canton of Aargau was granted.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] On 24 September 1856, the Swiss Federal Council granted them full political rights within Aargau, as well as broad business rights; however the majority Christian population did not fully abide by these new liberal laws.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The time of 1860 saw the canton government voting to grant suffrage in all local rights and to give their communities autonomy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Before the law was enacted, it was however repealed due to vocal opposition led by the Ultramonte Party.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Finally, the federal authorities in July 1863, granted all Jews full rights of citizens.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] However, they did not receive all of the rights in Endingen and Lengnau until a resolution of the Grand Council, on 15 May 1877, granted citizens' rights to the members of the Jewish communities of those places, giving them charters under the names of New Endingen and New Lengnau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The *Swiss Jewish Kulturverein* was instrumental in this fight from its founding in 1862 until it was dissolved 20 years later.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] During this period of diminished rights, they were not even allowed to bury their dead in Swiss soil and had to bury their dead on an island called *Judenäule* (Jews' Isle) on the Rhine near Waldshut.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Beginning in 1603, the deceased Jews of the Surbtal communities were buried on the river island which was leased by the Jewish community.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As the island was repeatedly flooded and devastated, in 1750 the Surbtal Jews asked the *Tagsatzung* to establish the Endingen cemetery in the vicinity of their communities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The capital of the canton is Aarau, which is located on its western border, on the Aare.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The canton borders Germany (Baden-Württemberg) to the north, the Rhine forming the border.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] To the west lie the Swiss cantons of Basel-Landschaft, Solothurn and Bern; the canton of Lucerne lies south, and Zürich and Zug to the east.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Its total area is 1,404 square kilometers (542 sq mi).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Besides the Rhine, it contains two large rivers, the Aare and the Reuss.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The canton of Aargau is one of the least mountainous Swiss cantons, forming part of the Swiss Plateau, to the north of the Alps and the east of the Jura, above which rises low hills.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Slightly over one-third of the canton is wooded (518 square kilometers (200 sq mi)), while nearly half is used from farming (635.7 square kilometers (245.4 sq mi)).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] 33.5 square kilometers (12.9 sq mi) or about 2.4% of the canton is considered unproductive, mostly lakes (notably Lake Hallwil) and streams.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] With a population density of 450/km2 (1,200/sq mi), the canton has a relatively high amount of land used for human development, with 216.7 square kilometers (83.7 sq mi) or about 15% of the canton developed for housing or transportation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It contains the hot sulphur springs of Baden and Schinznach-Bad, while at Rheinfelden there are very extensive saline springs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Just below Brugg the Reuss and the Limmat join the Aar, while around Brugg are the ruined castle of Habsburg, the old convent of Königsfelden (with fine painted medieval glass) and the remains of the Roman settlement of Vindonissa (Windisch).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Fahr Monastery forms a small exclave of the canton, otherwise surrounded by the canton of Zürich, and since 2008 is part of the Aargau municipality of Würenlos.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The most recent change in district boundaries occurred in 2010 when Hottwil transferred from Brugg to Laufenburg, following its merger with other municipalities, all of which were in Laufenburg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There are (as of 2026) 196 municipalities in the canton of Aargau.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As with most Swiss cantons there has been a trend since the early 2000s for municipalities to merge, though mergers in Aargau have so far been less radical than in other cantons.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The flag and arms of the canton of Aargau date to 1803 and are an original design by Samuel Ringier-Seelmatter; the current official design, specifying the stars as five-pointed, dates to 1930.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Aargau has a population (as of December 2020) of 694,072.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2010, 21.5% of the population are resident foreign nationals.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Over the last 10 years (2000–2010) the population has changed at a rate of 11%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Migration accounted for 8.7%, while births and deaths accounted for 2.8%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Most of the population (as of 2000) speaks German (477,093 or 87.1%) as their first language, Italian is the second most common (17,847 or 3.3%) and Serbo-Croatian is the third (10,645 or 1.9%).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There are 4,151 people who speak French and 618 people who speak Romansh.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Of the population in the canton, 146,421 or about 26.7% were born in Aargau and lived there in 2000.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were 140,768 or 25.7% who were born in the same canton, while 136,865 or 25.0% were born somewhere else in Switzerland, and 107,396 or 19.6% were born outside of Switzerland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2000, children and teenagers (0–19 years old) make up 24.3% of the population, while adults (20–64 years old) make up 62.3% and seniors (over 64 years old) make up 13.4%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2000, there were 227,656 people who were single and never married in the canton.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were 264,939 married individuals, 27,603 widows or widowers and 27,295 individuals who are divorced.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2000, there were 224,128 private households in the canton, and an average of 2.4 persons per household.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were 69,062 households that consist of only one person and 16,254 households with five or more people.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2009, the construction rate of new housing units was 6.5 new units per 1000 residents.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The vacancy rate for the canton, in 2010, was 1.54%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The majority of the population is centered on one of three areas: the Aare Valley, the side branches of the Aare Valley, or along the Rhine.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In the 2011 federal election, the most popular party was the SVP which received 34.7% of the vote.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The next three most popular parties were the SP/PS (18.0%), the FDP (11.5%) and the CVP (10.6%).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The SVP received about the same percentage of the vote as they did in the 2007 Federal election (36.2% in 2007 vs 34.7% in 2011).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The SPS retained about the same popularity (17.9% in 2007), the FDP retained about the same popularity (13.6% in 2007) and the CVP retained about the same popularity (13.5% in 2007).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] "*" indicates that the party was not on the ballot in this canton.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] CVP and BDP merged to form The Centre party.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The Grand Council of the canton of Aargau is called Grosser Rat.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] It is the legislature of the canton, has 140 seats, with members elected every four years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] From the 2000 census, 219,800 or 40.1% were Roman Catholic, while 189,606 or 34.6% belonged to the Swiss Reformed Church.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were 342 individuals (or about 0.06% of the population) who were Jewish, and 30,072 (or about 5.49% of the population) who were Muslim.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] There were 1,463 individuals who were Buddhist, 2,089 individuals who were Hindu and 495 individuals who belonged to another church.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] 57,573 (or about 10.52% of the population) belonged to no church, are agnostic or atheist, and 15,875 individuals (or about 2.90% of the population) did not answer the question.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In Aargau about 212,069 or (38.7%) of the population have completed non-mandatory upper secondary education, and 70,896 or (12.9%) have completed additional higher education (either university or a *Fachhochschule*).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Of the 70,896 who completed tertiary schooling, 63.6% were Swiss men, 20.9% were Swiss women, 10.4% were non-Swiss men and 5.2% were non-Swiss women.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2010, Aargau had an unemployment rate of 3.6%.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As of 2008, there were 11,436 people employed in the primary economic sector and about 3,927 businesses involved in this sector.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] 95,844 people were employed in the secondary sector and there were 6,055 businesses in this sector.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] 177,782 people were employed in the tertiary sector, with 21,530 businesses in this sector.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] In 2008 the total number of full-time equivalent jobs was 238,225.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The number of jobs in the primary sector was 7,167, of which 6,731 were in agriculture, 418 were in forestry or lumber production and 18 were in fishing or fisheries.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The number of jobs in the secondary sector was 90,274 of which 64,089 or (71.0%) were in manufacturing, 366 or (0.4%) were in mining and 21,705 (24.0%) were in construction.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The number of jobs in the tertiary sector was 140,784.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Of the working population, 19.5% used public transportation to get to work, and 55.3% used a private car.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Public transportation – bus and train – is provided by Busbetrieb Aarau AG.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The farmland of the canton of Aargau is some of the most fertile in Switzerland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Dairy farming, cereal and fruit farming are among the canton's main economic activities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The canton is also industrially developed, particularly in the fields of electrical engineering, precision instruments, iron, steel, cement and textiles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Three of Switzerland's five nuclear power plants are in the canton of Aargau (Beznau I + II and Leibstadt).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Additionally, the many rivers supply enough water for numerous hydroelectric power plants throughout the canton.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] The canton of Aargau is often called "the energy canton".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] A significant number of people commute into the financial center of the city of Zürich, which is just across the cantonal border.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] As such the per capita cantonal income (in 2005) is 49,209 CHF.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Tourism is significant, particularly for the hot springs at Baden and Schinznach-Bad, the ancient castles, the landscape, and the many old museums in the canton.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/aargau] Hillwalking is another tourist attraction but is of only limited significance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Among other factors, the Baltic German nobility was more willing to abolish serfdom than Russian nobility and thus Baltic governorates became the testing ground for entire Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The book was promptly translated into French, Danish and Russian.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the War of 1812 and the French invasion of Kurzeme, Emperor Alexander I established a commission to improve the legal status of the peasants in Kurzeme.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In 1814, Garlieb Merkel submitted an economic study on the benefits of employing free peasants as opposed to the work of commoners to the tender announced by the Free Economic Society, which justified the abolition of serfdom in the Baltic provinces.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In the Livonian Confederation, farmers living in the castle districts retained personal freedom and self-government, but were forced to perform military and civilian duties and pay taxes.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the devastation caused by the Livonian War, the political influence and power of the manor owners increased over the peasants.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the Duchy of Livonia and Duchy of Courland and Semigallia came under the rule of the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, most peasants lost their personal freedom and became the "movable" property of the nobles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] However, personal freedom was maintained by free peasants (Vidzeme leimans and Curonian Kings), as well as city residents.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Curonian Kings was the inhabitants of seven villages of Kurzeme (Ķoniņi, Pliķi, Kalēju, Ziemeļu, Viesalga, Sausgaļi and Dragūnai), who had received special county books from masters of the Livonian Order.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In legal terms, the royals were no different from the nobles, they did not pay regular dues and did not comply with the clauses, and they were the complete determinants of the land they cultivated themselves or with the help of paid labor.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Like the nobles, the Curonian Kings had the rights of fishing, hunting, own and use mills, as well as their own coats of arms.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Since Livonian nobility provided much needed resources to support Sweden's wars it had sufficient leverage to maintain laws and social order as they see fit.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Once Livonia, Estonia and Duchy of Courland and Semigallia became part of Russian Empire local voices for abolition of serfdom emerged.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Among the first were pastor Johann Georg Eisen von Schwarzenberg and Garlieb Merkel.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Russian Empress Catherine the Great had annulled an act by Peter III that essentially freed the serfs belonging to the Orthodox Church.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] She also tried to take away serfs right to petition her.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Far away from the capital, serfs were confused as to the circumstances of her accession to the throne.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Pugachev's Rebellion of 1774 pushed Empress away from the idea of serf liberation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] During Catherine's reign (1762–1796), despite her enlightened ideals, the serfs were generally unhappy and discontented.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In October 1802, widespread Kauguri riots took place in the vicinity of Valmiera, which were suppressed only by troops.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After investigating the causes of the peasant uprising, new peasants' laws were issued in 1804, which determined that the peasants were attributed to the manor's parish and not to the landowner.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law determined the status of farmers, and the court system was reformed (parish court, land court, criminal court).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In addition, in 1809, "Additional Points to the Farmers' Law" were issued.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In 1805, this law also came into force for the peasants of the Governorate of Estonia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Livonian Peasants Act of 1804 in effect replaced serfdom with villeinage.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Similar law was enacted with Estonian Peasants Act of 1804.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Analogous Peasantry Laws were approved by Landtags (Diet of knighthood) of the governorate of Estonia in 1816, governorate of Courland in 1817 and the governorate of Livonia in 1819 and then all has been confirmed by emperor Alexander I of Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] On 23 May 1816 the Livonian Peasant Law was adopted and came into force in 1819, abolishing serfdom; the peasantry could also acquire real estate; financial leasing was introduced as a burden.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Peasant communities were to create municipalities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After a long debate, in April 1817, the Landtag of Kurzeme adopted a decision on the release of the peasants, which was approved on 25 August 1817 and announced at a solemn ceremony in the presence of Emperor Alexander I on 30 August 1818 in Jelgava.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Kurzeme Farmers' Release Law formally gave personal freedom and freedom of movement to 300,000 people.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] On 26 March 1819, a similar law was approved by Vidzeme Landtag, it was promulgated on 6 January 1820 in Riga and Sāmsala.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] However, the abolition of marital status took place gradually, the so-called temporary status was established.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] With the release of the farmers, a change in the lowest administrative structure was also envisaged.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the release, for 3 years the farmers were not allowed to leave the boundaries of their parish district, but for the next 3 - the boundaries of the district of the mayor (in Kurzeme) or the boundaries of the district of the lord (Vidzeme).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Only in 1832 did Jurģi farmers gained the right to change their place of residence within the boundaries of their province, but in Kurzeme until 1848, farmers were not allowed to settle in cities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the release of the peasants in 1820, Merkel published an essay dedicated to Alexander I, "Free Latvians and Estonians".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] For this, as well as for other works dedicated to the release of peasants, the monarch granted the author a lifetime pension of 300 silver rubles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Livonian Peasants' Law of 1849 came into force 1850. from the autumn of 1849, after publication in Estonian and Latvian.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law confirmed that the entire land was the property of the manor, but determined how it was to be used.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] That part of the land which had hitherto been at the disposal of the peasants was declared farmland, the use of which was in accordance with the free contract.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] It could be rented out as viable farms, preferably for money or sold to the peasants for real.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law also regulated compulsory schooling.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The maintenance of the schools remained the responsibility of the municipalities, with Lutherans having to bear their own and Orthodox their own schools.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] A new link for the management of Lutheran peasant schools was the parish school government, which included a landowner, pastor, a parish school teacher and one municipality judges.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The management of the Orthodox schools remained the responsibility of the Orthodox Church and the Synod.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The ***Acte de déchéance de l'Empereur*** (from French: "Emperor's Demise Act") was a law passed by the Sénat conservateur on 2 April 1814, which deposed Napoleon I as Emperor of the French.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Since the French Revolution had deposed Louis XVI, France had been almost constantly at war with most of Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Chronic political instability and the constant rumbles of war created a favourable terrain for a military coup, which General Bonaparte exploited on 18 Brumaire, establishing the French Consulate in the Constitution of the Year VIII, led by an equilateral triumvirate.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Two years later, the Constitution was amended into the Constitution of the Year X, making Bonaparte First Consul for life.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Finally, on 18 May 1804, the Sénat conservateur passed the Constitution of the Year XII. establishing an Emperor, Bonaparte, styling himself "Napoléon I, Emperor of the French".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Napoleon was crowned emperor on 2 December 1804, inaugurating the First French Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] A series of Napoleon's disasters and conflicts like the Peninsular War, the War of the Sixth Coalition, and the French invasion of Russia led to the near obliteration of the once overwhelming Grande Armée.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] By February 1814, the French Army was so depleted that, even after winning every battle of the Six Days' Campaign, it could not stop the march of the Allies on French soil on its route on Paris.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The Allies arrived at the outskirts of Paris in late March, and Talleyrand maneuvered to take upon himself to negotiate the capitulation of Marmont, who defended the capital.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] On 31 March, Talleyrand dined at his hotel with Frederick William III of Prussia and Alexander I of Russia, and pleaded for a Bourbon restoration, arguing that the Senate would support the plan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] On 1 April 1814, the Sénat conservateur elected Talleyrand chief of a five-member provisionary government.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The next morning, Talleyrand and Barthélemy, president of the Senate, proposed a motion to depose Napoléon and the House of Bonaparte, and call the Count of Provence to the throne as King Louis XVIII.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] On 3 April, the Senate voted a text detailing its reasons for ousting Napoléon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] It charged the emperor with numerous violations of the Constitution of the Year XII, which it had itself approved over the years.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The minutes of the meeting were published in *Le Moniteur Universel* of 4 April.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The final paragraph read: The Senate declares and decrees as follows: 1.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Napoleon Buonaparte is cast down from the throne, and the right of succession in his family is abolished.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The French people and army are absolved from their oath of fidelity to him.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The present decree shall be transmitted to the departments and armies, and proclaimed immediately in all the quarters of the capital.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] On 11 April, after attempting to put his son on the throne, Napoléon abdicated unconditionally.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] The Allies allowed him to keep his title of Emperor, but exiled him to Elba.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Napoléon attempted to return to power on 26 February 1815, leading to the Hundred Days.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] He was defeated at the Battle of Waterloo and imprisoned to the remote rock of Saint Helena for life.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] In the following years, the Acte de déchéance de l'Empereur served as a litmus test of allegiance to the House of Bourbon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] *"Extrait des registres du Sénat-Conservateur. - Séance du dimanche 3 avril 1814, présidée par M. le sénateur comte Barthélemy".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/acte-de-déchéance-de-l-empereur] Archived from the original on 2016-03-04.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Prince **Adam Jerzy Czartoryski** (14 January 1770 – 15 July 1861), also known as **Adam George Czartoryski**, was a Polish nobleman, statesman, diplomat and author who served as Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The son of a wealthy prince, he began his political career as a foreign minister to Emperor Alexander I of Russia after Poland was partitioned by Russia, Prussia and Austria.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He later became a leader of the Polish government in exile during and after the failed November Uprising 1830–1831 and a bitter opponent of Alexander I's successor, Nicholas I.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In exile, he advocated for the reestablishment of a sovereign Polish state, which also stimulated early Balkan and Belgian nationalism, and intensified their desire for independence.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was a dedicated patron of arts and greatly contributed to the Czartoryski Collection.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1798, he purchased one of Poland's most important national treasures – Leonardo da Vinci's *Lady with an Ermine*, which he brought as a gift for his mother, Princess Izabela Czartoryska from Italy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski was born on 14 January 1770 in Warsaw.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was the son of Prince Adam Kazimierz Czartoryski and Countess Izabela von Flemming.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] It was rumoured that Adam was the fruit of a liaison between Izabela and Russian ambassador to Poland, Nikolai Repnin.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, Repnin left the country two years before Adam Czartoryski was born, but Empress Catherine II dismissed Nikolai Repnin from his post on 10 April 1769.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His half-siblings were Teresa Czartoryski (1765–1780), Maria Anna Czartoryski, Konstanty Adam Czartoryski, Gabriella Czartoryski (d.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After careful education at home by eminent specialists, mostly French, he went abroad in 1786.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At Gotha, Czartoryski heard Johann Wolfgang von Goethe read his *Iphigenia in Tauris* and made the acquaintance of the dignified Johann Gottfried Herder and the "fat little Christoph Martin Wieland".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1789, Czartoryski visited Great Britain with his mother and was present at the trial of Warren Hastings.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On a second visit in 1793, he made many acquaintances among the British aristocracy and studied the British constitution.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In the interval between these visits, he fought for Poland during the Polish–Russian War of 1792, which preceded the Second Partition of Poland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was one of the early recipients of the *Virtuti Militari* decoration for valour there.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was arrested on his way to Poland at Brussels by the Austrian government.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After the Third Partition of Poland, the Czartoryski estates were confiscated, and in May 1795, Adam and his younger brother Konstanty Adam were summoned to Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Later in 1795, the two brothers were commanded to enter Imperial Russian army military service.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam became an officer in the horse guards and Konstanty in the foot guards.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Catherine the Great was so favourably impressed by the youths that she restored them part of their estates and in early 1796 made them gentlemen-in-waiting, courtiers.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was already connected with the imperial family.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His elder sister Maria Anna was married to the then-Grand Duchess Maria Feodorovna's brother, Duke Louis of Württemberg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On the accession of Emperor Paul I, Czartoryski was appointed adjutant to Alexander, who was now *Tsarevich*, and was permitted to revisit his Polish estates for three months.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At this time, the tone of the Russian court was relatively liberal.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Political reformers, including Pyotr Volkonsky and Nikolay Novosiltsev, possessed great influence on the tsar.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was not only close with Tsarevich Alexander, but Alexander's wife, the Grand Duchess, Tsarevna Elizabeth Alexeievna as well.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Born Princess Louise of Baden, she was married to the Grand Duke Alexander at the age of fourteen, and though she and Alexander shared a friendly bond, Alexander sought romantic comfort elsewhere.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Elizabeth Alexeievna soon fell in love with Czartoryski, who reciprocated her feelings.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After Elizabeth gave birth to a baby girl on 29 May 1799, the Grand Duchess Maria Alexandrovna, the Tsar Paul I didn't hide his suspicions, with both Elizabeth and Alexander having fair hair, and the baby having dark hair.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was then sent on a diplomatic mission to the court of Charles Emmanuel IV of Sardinia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On reaching Italy, Czartoryski found that that monarch was a king without a kingdom and so the outcome of his first diplomatic mission was a pleasant tour through Italy to Naples, the acquisition of the Italian language and a careful exploration of the antiquities of Rome.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In the spring of 1801, the new emperor, Alexander I, summoned his friend back to Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski found the emperor still suffering from remorse at his father's assassination and could do nothing but talk about religion and politics to a small circle of friends.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Against all remonstrances, he replied only, "There's plenty of time".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Emperor Alexander I appointed Czartoryski administrator of the Educational District of Vilna (Polish: Wilno, Lithuanian: Vilnius) and curator of the Vilna Academy (3 April 1803) so that he might give full play to his advanced ideas.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He greatly improved the Polish education system.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was to keep those function until 1824.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski paid most attention to foreign affairs; as the emperor's key advisor, he exercised practical control of Russian diplomacy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His first act had been to protest energetically against Napoleon's murder of a Bourbon royal prince, the Duke of Enghien 20 March 1804, and to insist on an immediate rupture with the government of the French Revolution, which was under Napoléon Bonaparte, whom the emperor considered a regicide.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 7 June 1804, the French minister, Gabriel Marie Joseph, Comte d'Hédouville, left Saint Petersburg, and on 11 August a note, dictated by Czartoryski to Alexander I, was sent to the Russian minister in London to urge the formation of an anti-French coalition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] It was also Czartoryski who framed the Convention of 6 November 1804 whereby Russia agreed to put 115,000 and Austria 235,000, men in the field against Napoleon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Finally, in April 1805, he signed an offensive-defensive alliance with George III's United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski's most striking ministerial act, however, was a memorial written in 1805, otherwise undated, which aimed at transforming the whole map of Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Austria and Prussia were to divide Germany between them.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Russia was to acquire the Dardanelles, the Sea of Marmora, the Bosporus with Constantinople and Corfu.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Austria was to have Bosnia , Wallachia and Ragusa.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Montenegro, enlarged by Mostar and the Ionian Islands, was to form a separate state.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The United Kingdom and Russia together were to maintain the equilibrium of the world.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In return for their acquisitions in Germany, Austria and Prussia were to consent to the creation of an autonomous Polish state extending from Danzig (Gdańsk) to the sources of the Vistula under the protection of Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] That plan presented the best guarantee at the time for the independent existence of Poland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, in the meantime, Austria had come to an understanding with Britain about subsidies, and war had begun.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1805 Adam Jerzy Czartoryski accompanied Alexander I to Berlin and to Olomouc, Moravia (now Czech Republic), as chief minister.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He regarded the Berlin visit as a blunder, chiefly due to his distrust of Prussia, but Alexander ignored his representations, and in February 1807 Czartoryski lost favour and was superseded by Andrei Budberg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Though no longer a minister, Czartoryski continued still to enjoy Alexander I's confidence in private, and in 1810, the Emperor candidly admitted to Czartoryski that in 1805 he had been in error and that had not made proper use of Czartoryski's opportunities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The same year, Czartoryski left Saint Petersburg forever, but the personal relations between him and Alexander I were never better.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] They met again as friends at Kalisz (Greater Poland) shortly before the signing of the Russo-Prussian alliance on 20 February 1813, and Czartoryski was in the emperor's suite at Paris in 1814 and rendered him material services at the Congress of Vienna.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the Congress of Vienna, Alexander I had also been asked to agree to a divorce for the Empress Elizabeth so that she could marry Czartoryski.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was content with the title of senator-palatine and a role in the administration.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The wedding led to a duel with his rival, Ludwik Pac.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On his father's death in 1823, Czartoryski retired to his ancestral Czartoryski Palace at Puławy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1824 he lost the charge of curator of the Wilno University, in relation with the Philomaths trial.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, the 29 November 1830 uprising brought him back to public life.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He became president of the provisional government established on 3 December and summoned on 18 December 1830 the *Sejm* of 1831, which chose General Chlopicki as dictator.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After Chlopicki's resignation on 18 January and the dethroning by the Sejm of Nicolas I as king of Poland on 25 January, Czartoryski was elected chief of the Polish National Government by 121 out of 138 votes on 30 January 1831.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In August 1831, the military situation was bad.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] General Ivan Paskevich was approaching Warsaw from the West and the commander-in-chief, General Jan Zygmunt Skrzynecki was dismissed on 9 August.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 15 and 16 August, there were riots in Warsaw, and many imprisoned supposed traitors, notably two generals, were hanged.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski decided to resign from the government after he had sacrificed half of his fortune to the national cause.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was replaced by General Jan Krukowiecki as both head of the government and commander in chief.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Yet the sexagenarian statesman continued to display great energy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 23 August 1831, he joined Italian General Girolamo Ramorino's army corps as a volunteer and subsequently formed a confederation of the three southern provinces of Kalisz, Sandomierz and Kraków.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the war's end, when the uprising was crushed by the Russians — Warsaw was taken on 8 September — he fled under false identity to the Cracow Republic, then in Austria, and from there could reach England.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Afterwards, he was sentenced to death, though the sentence was soon commuted to exile.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 25 February 1832, while in the United Kingdom, he kept advancing the Polish cause and with the help of influential friends, many of them Scottish, inspired the creation of the Literary Association of the Friends of Poland, based in London, but with branches in Glasgow, Birmingham and Hull.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] That same year, Czartoryski left England for France, taking up residence in Paris.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] As a magnate and arguably the most considerable Polish-émigré figure of the time – Czartoryski was Chairman of the Polish National Uprising Government, and leader of a political emigre party.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Thousands of Poles had emigrated to France in the Great Emigration.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski was an active leader of the mushrooming committees that were formed to maintain political momentum and salvage Polish cultural heritage in the exile community.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was the founding chairman, in April 1832, of a Historical and Literary Society.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1838 he became the legal owner and founding president (for life) of the Polish Library in Paris, the first repository of polonica, books, and archives outside the territory of Poland, which had secured, with French public support, a building on the Ile Saint-Louis in the heart of Paris.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1843 he bought the Hôtel Lambert on the Île Saint-Louis and his political faction came to be identified by his private address, simply as the *Hôtel Lambert*.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His tireless efforts on behalf of Poland continued well into his seventies: in 1842 he conceived a project to found a Polish settlement in rural Turkey.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski wanted to create a second emigration centre there, after the first one in Paris.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He sent his representative, Michał Czajkowski, to Turkey and purchased a forest area which encompasses present-day Adampol from the missionary order of Lazarists.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The settlement was named Adam-koj (Adamköy) after its founder, in Turkish, the "Village of Adam", whereas in Polish it was referred to as "Adampol".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Polonezköy or Adampol survives to this day as a small village on the Asian side of Istanbul, about 30 kilometres from the historic city centre.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At its inception, the village was inhabited by just 12 people, while at its peak, there were no more than 220 people.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Over time, Adampol developed and became populated by emigrants from the unsuccessful 1848 Revolution, the Crimean War in 1853, and by escapees from Siberia and from captivity in Circassia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The Polish villagers engaged in agriculture, animal husbandry and forestry.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After the November Uprising in 1830–1831 until his death, Czartoryski supported the idea of resurrecting an updated Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth on federal principles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The visionary statesman and former friend, confidant and *de facto* foreign minister of Russia's Emperor Alexander I acted as the "uncrowned king and unacknowledged foreign minister" of a non-existent Poland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was disappointed when the hopes that had he held as late as the Congress of Vienna of Alexander I undertaking reforms failed to materialise.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His subsequent thoughts were distilled in a book, completed in 1827 but published only in 1830, *Essai sur la diplomatie* (Essay on Diplomacy).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] According to the historian Marian Kamil Dziewanowski, it is indispensable to an understanding of the Prince's many activities conducted in Paris following the ill-fated Polish November 1830 Uprising.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski wanted to find a place for Poland in the Europe of the time.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He sought to interest Western Europeans in the adversities facing his stateless nation, which he still considered to be an indispensable part of the European political structure.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adhering to the Polish motto, "for our freedom and yours", Czartoryski connected Polish efforts for independence with similar movements in other subjugated nations of Europe and in the East as far as the Caucasus.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Thanks to his private initiative and generosity, the émigrés of his subjugated nation conducted a foreign policy often on a broader scale than had the old Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Of particular interest are Czartoryski's observations, in his *Essay on Diplomacy*, regarding Russia's role in the world.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Above all, he aspired to reconstitute – with French, British and Turkish support – a Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth federated with the Czechs, Slovaks, Hungarians, Romanians and all the South Slavs of the future Yugoslavia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Poland, according to his vision, could have mediated the conflicts between Hungary and the Slavs, and between Hungary and Romania.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the same time, the Belgian people were also seeking independence.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski died aged 91 at his country residence east of Paris, at Montfermeil, near Meaux, on 15 July 1861.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski's principal works, as cited in the 1911 *Encyclopædia Britannica*, are *Essai sur la diplomatie* (Marseilles, 1830); *Life of J.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Niemcewicz* (Paris, 1860); *Alexander I. et Czartoryski: correspondence ... et conversations* (1801–1823) (Paris, 1865); *Memoires et correspondence avec Alex.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] I.*, with preface by C. de Mazade, 2 vols.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] (Paris, 1887); an English translation, *Memoirs of Czartoryski, &c.*, edited by A.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Gielguch, with documents relating to his negotiations with Pitt, and conversations with Palmerston in 1832 (2 vols., London, 1888).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The 1975–1976 academic year at the College of Europe was named in his honour.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski makes a cameo appearance in volume 3 of Leo Tolstoy's novel, *War and Peace*, at an Allied Council conference that takes place at Olomouc, Moravia on 18 November 1805, just before the Battle of Austerlitz.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adolphe-roehn] Roehn exhibited his work in the Paris Salon from Salon of 1799 to 1866, winning a second class medal at the Salon of 1819.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adolphe-roehn] Between 1802 and 1814, under the direction of Baron Vivant Denon, the director of the Louvre, he created a series of drawings illustrating Napoleon's campaigns in Italy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adolphe-roehn] After the bloody Battle of Eylau in 1807, Vivant Denon held a propaganda contest requiring entrants depict a certain scene from the event.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adolphe-roehn] Roehn received a "gold medal of encouragement" (the winning entry was *Napoléon on the Battlefield of Eylau* by Antoine-Jean Gros).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/adolphe-roehn] Like his son, Jean Alphonse Roehn, he taught drawing at the Louis-Legrand School.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The eldest son of Paul I of Russia and Sophie Dorothea of Württemberg, Alexander succeeded to the throne after his father was murdered.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] As prince and during the early years of his reign, he often used liberal rhetoric but continued Russia's absolutist policies in practice.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the first years of his reign, he initiated some minor social reforms and (in 1803–1804) major liberal educational reforms, such as building more universities.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander appointed Mikhail Speransky, the son of a village priest, as one of his closest advisors.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The over-centralised Collegium ministries were abolished and replaced by the Committee of Ministers, State Council, and the Supreme Court to improve the legal system.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Plans were made, but never consummated, to set up a parliament and sign a constitution.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In contrast to his westernising predecessors, such as Peter the Great, Alexander was a Russian nationalist and Slavophile who wanted Russia to develop on the basis of Russian rather than European culture.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In foreign policy, he changed Russia's position towards France four times between 1804 and 1812, shifting among neutrality, opposition, and alliance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1805 he joined Britain in the War of the Third Coalition against Napoleon, but after suffering massive defeats at the battles of Austerlitz and Friedland, he switched sides and formed an alliance with Napoleon in the Treaty of Tilsit (1807) and joined Napoleon's Continental System.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He fought a small-scale naval war against Britain between 1807 and 1812 and took Finland from Sweden in 1809 after Sweden's refusal to join the Continental System.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander and Napoleon hardly agreed, especially regarding Poland, and the alliance collapsed by 1810.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander's greatest triumph came in 1812 when Napoleon's invasion of Russia descended into a catastrophe for the French.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] As part of the winning coalition against Napoleon, he gained territory in Poland.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He formed the Holy Alliance to suppress the revolutionary movements in Europe, which he saw as immoral threats to legitimate Christian monarchs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] During the second half of his reign, Alexander became increasingly arbitrary, reactionary, and fearful of plots against him; as a result, he ended many of the reforms he had made earlier in his reign.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He purged schools of foreign teachers, as education became more religiously driven as well as politically conservative.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Speransky was replaced as advisor with the strict artillery inspector Aleksey Arakcheyev, who oversaw the creation of military settlements.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander died of typhus in December 1825 while on a trip to southern Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He left no legitimate children, as his two daughters died in childhood.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Neither of his brothers wanted to become emperor.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After a period of great confusion (that presaged the failed Decembrist revolt of liberal army officers in the weeks after his death), he was succeeded by his younger brother, Nicholas I of Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander was born at 10:45, on 23 December 1777 in Saint Petersburg, and he and his younger brother Constantine were raised by their grandmother, Catherine.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He was baptized on 31 December in the Grand Church of the Winter Palace by mitred archpriest Ioann Ioannovich Panfilov (confessor of Empress Catherine II).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His godmother was Catherine the Great, and his godfathers were Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor, and Frederick the Great.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He was named after Alexander Nevsky, the patron saint of Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Andrey Afanasyevich Samborsky, whom his grandmother chose to be his religious instructor, was an atypical, unbearded Orthodox priest.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Samborsky had long lived in England and taught Alexander and his brother Constantine excellent English, a very uncommon accomplishment for potential Russian autocrats of the time.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 9 October 1793, when Alexander was still 15 years old, he married 14-year-old Princess Louise of Baden, who took the name Elizabeth Alexeievna.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His grandmother was the one who presided over his marriage to the young princess.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Until his grandmother's death, he was constantly walking the line of allegiance between his grandmother and his father.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His steward, Nikolai Saltykov, helped him navigate the political landscape, engendering dislike for his grandmother and dread in dealing with his father.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Catherine had the Alexander Palace built for the couple.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] This did nothing to help his relationship with her, as Catherine would go out of her way to amuse them with dancing and parties, which annoyed his wife.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Living at the palace also put pressure on him to perform as a husband, though he felt only a brother's love for the Grand Duchess.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He began to sympathise more with his father, as he saw visiting his father's fiefdom at Gatchina Palace as a relief from the ostentatious court of the empress.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] There, they wore simple Prussian military uniforms, instead of the gaudy clothing popular at the French court they had to wear when visiting Catherine.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Even so, visiting the tsarevich did not come without a bit of travail.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Paul liked to have his guests perform military drills, which he also pushed upon his sons, Alexander and Constantine.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He was also prone to fits of temper, and he often went into fits of rage when events did not go his way.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Some sources allege that the empress Catherine planned to remove her son Paul from the succession altogether (in consideration of his unstable temperament and bizarre personality traits) and make Alexander her successor instead.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Catherine's death in November 1796 brought her son Paul to the throne before she could appoint Alexander as her successor.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander disliked his father as emperor even more than he did his grandmother.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He wrote that Russia had become a "plaything for the insane" and that "absolute power disrupts everything".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It is likely that seeing two previous rulers abuse their autocratic powers in such a way pushed him to be one of the more progressive Romanov tsars of the 19th century.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the country as a whole, Paul was widely unpopular.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He accused his wife of conspiring to become another Catherine and seize power from him as his mother did from his father.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He also suspected Alexander of conspiring against him.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander became Emperor of Russia when his father was assassinated on 23 March 1801.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander, then 23 years old, was in the Saint Michael's Castle at the moment of the assassination and his accession to the throne was announced by General Nicholas Zubov, one of the assassins.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Historians still debate Alexander's role in his father's murder.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The most common theory is that he was let into the conspirators' secret and was willing to take the throne, but insisted that his father should not be killed.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Becoming emperor through a crime that cost his father's life would give Alexander a strong sense of remorse and shame.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander I succeeded to the throne that day and was crowned in the Kremlin on 15 September of that year.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Orthodox Church initially exercised little influence on Alexander's life.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The young emperor was determined to reform the inefficient, highly centralised systems of government that Russia relied upon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A few years into his reign, the liberal Mikhail Speransky became one of the Emperor's closest advisors, and he drew up elaborate plans for reforms.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the Government reform, the old Collegia were abolished and new Ministries were created in their place, led by ministers responsible to the Crown.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A Committee of Ministers under the chairmanship of the Sovereign dealt with all interdepartmental matters.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The State Council was created to improve the technique of legislation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It was intended to become the Second Chamber of a representative legislature.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Governing Senate was reorganised as the Supreme Court of the Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The codification of the laws initiated in 1801 was never carried out during his reign.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander wanted to resolve another crucial issue in Russia, the status of the serfs, although this was not achieved until 1861 (during the reign of his nephew Alexander II).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His advisors quietly discussed the options at length.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Cautiously, he extended the right to own land to most classes of subjects, including state-owned peasants, in 1801 and created a new social category of "free ploughman", for peasants voluntarily emancipated by their masters, in 1803.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The great majority of serfs were not affected.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] When Alexander's reign began, there were three universities in Russia, at Moscow, Vilna (Vilnius), and Dorpat (Tartu).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] These were strengthened, and three others were founded at Saint Petersburg, Kharkiv, and Kazan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Literary and scientific bodies were established or encouraged, and his reign became noted for the aid lent to the sciences and arts by the Emperor and the wealthy nobility.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander later expelled foreign scholars.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After 1815, the military settlements (farms worked by soldiers and their families under military control) were introduced, with the idea of making the army, or part of it, self-supporting economically and for providing it with recruits.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Called both an autocrat and Jacobin, a man of the world and a mystic, Alexander appeared to his contemporaries as a riddle which each read according to his own temperament.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon Bonaparte thought him a "shifty Byzantine", and called him the Talma of the North, as ready to play any conspicuous part.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] To Klemens von Metternich, he was a madman to be humoured.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1803, Beethoven dedicated his Opus 30 Violin Sonata to Alexander who in response gave the famous composer a diamond at the Congress of Vienna where they met in 1814.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Upon his accession, Alexander reversed many of the unpopular policies of his father, Paul, denounced the League of Armed Neutrality, and made peace with Britain (April 1801).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] At the same time, he opened negotiations with Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Soon afterwards, at Memel, he entered into a close alliance with Prussia, not as he boasted from motives of policy, but in the spirit of true chivalry, out of friendship for the young King Frederick William III of Prussia and his beautiful wife Louise of Mecklenburg-Strelitz.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The development of this alliance was interrupted by the short-lived peace of October 1801, and for a while it seemed as though France and Russia might come to an understanding.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Carried away by the enthusiasm of Frédéric-César de La Harpe, who had returned to Russia from Paris, Alexander began openly to proclaim his admiration for French institutions and for the person of Napoleon Bonaparte.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] La Harpe, after a new visit to Paris, presented to Alexander his *Reflections on the True Nature of the Consul for Life*, which, as Alexander said, tore the veil from his eyes and revealed Bonaparte "as not a true patriot", but only as "the most famous tyrant the world has produced".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Later on, La Harpe and his friend Henri Monod lobbied Alexander, who persuaded the other Allied powers opposing Napoleon to recognise Vaudois and Argovian independence, in spite of Bern's attempts to reclaim them as *subject lands*.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander's disillusionment was completed by the execution of the Louis Antoine, Duke of Enghien on trumped up charges.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Russian court went into mourning for the last member of the Princes of Condé, and diplomatic relations with France were broken off.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander was especially alarmed and decided he had to somehow curb Napoleon's power.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In opposing Napoleon I, "the oppressor of Europe and the disturber of the world's peace," Alexander in fact already believed himself to be fulfilling a divine mission.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In his instructions to Niklolay Novosiltsev, his special envoy in London, the emperor elaborated the motives of his policy in language that appealed little to the prime minister, William Pitt the Younger.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Yet the document is of great interest, as it formulates for the first time in an official dispatch the ideals of international policy that were to play a conspicuous part in world affairs at the close of the revolutionary epoch.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander argued that the outcome of the war was not only to be the liberation of France, but the universal triumph of "the sacred rights of humanity".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A general treaty was to become the main basis of the relations of the states forming "the European Confederation".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] While he believed the effort would not attain universal peace, it would be worthwhile if it established clear principles for the prescriptions of the rights of nations.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The body would assure "the positive rights of nations" and "the privilege of neutrality", while asserting the obligation to exhaust all resources of mediation to retain peace, and would form "a new code of the law of nations".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Meanwhile, Napoleon never gave up hope of detaching him from the coalition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He had no sooner entered Vienna in triumph than he opened negotiations with Alexander; he resumed them after the Battle of Austerlitz (2 December).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Russia and France, he urged, were "geographical allies"; there was, and could be, between them no true conflict of interests; together they might rule the world.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] But Alexander was still determined "to persist in the system of disinterestedness in respect of all the states of Europe which he had thus far followed", and he again allied himself with the Kingdom of Prussia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The campaign of Jena and the Battle of Eylau followed; and Napoleon, though still intent on the Russian alliance, stirred up Poles, Turks and Persians to break the obstinacy of the Tsar.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A party too in Russia itself, headed by the Tsar's brother Constantine Pavlovich, was clamorous for peace; but Alexander, after a vain attempt to form a new coalition, summoned the Russian nation to a holy war against Napoleon as the enemy of the Orthodox faith.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The outcome was the rout of Friedland (13/14 June 1807).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Instead of demanding harsh peace terms, he offered to the chastened autocrat his alliance, and a partnership in his glory.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The two Emperors met at Tilsit on 25 June 1807.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon knew well how to appeal to the exuberant imagination of his new-found friend.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Nevertheless, a thought awoke in Alexander's impressionable mind an ambition to which he had hitherto been a stranger.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The interests of Europe as a whole were utterly forgotten.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The brilliance of these new visions did not, however, blind Alexander to the obligations of friendship, and he refused to retain the Danubian principalities as the price for suffering a further dismemberment of Prussia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] "We have made loyal war", he said, "we must make a loyal peace".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It was not long before the first enthusiasm of Tilsit began to wane.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The French remained in Prussia, the Russians on the Danube, and each accused the other of breach of faith.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Meanwhile, however, the personal relations of Alexander and Napoleon were of the most cordial character, and it was hoped that a fresh meeting might adjust all differences between them.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The meeting took place at Erfurt in October 1808 and resulted in a treaty that defined the common policy of the two Emperors.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] But Alexander's relations with Napoleon nonetheless suffered a change.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He realised that in Napoleon sentiment never got the better of reason, that as a matter of fact he had never intended his proposed "grand enterprise" seriously, and had only used it to preoccupy the mind of the Tsar while he consolidated his own power in Central Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] From this moment the French alliance was for Alexander also not a fraternal agreement to rule the world, but an affair of pure policy.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He used it initially to remove "the geographical enemy" from the gates of Saint Petersburg by wresting Finland from Sweden (1809), and he hoped further to make the Danube the southern frontier of Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Events were rapidly heading towards the rupture of the Franco-Russian alliance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] While Alexander assisted Napoleon in the War of the Fifth Coalition in 1809, he declared plainly that he would not allow the Austrian Empire to be crushed out of existence.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon subsequently complained bitterly of the inactivity of the Russian troops during the campaign.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The tsar in turn protested against Napoleon's encouragement of the Poles.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the matter of the French alliance he knew himself to be practically isolated in Russia, and he declared that he could not sacrifice the interest of his people and empire to his affection for Napoleon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] "I don't want anything for myself", he said to the French ambassador, "therefore the world is not large enough to come to an understanding on the affairs of Poland, if it is a question of its restoration".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] But if Alexander suspected Napoleon's intentions, Napoleon was no less suspicious of Alexander.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Partly to test his sincerity, Napoleon sent an almost peremptory request for the hand of the grand-duchess Anna Pavlovna, the tsar's youngest sister.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After some little delay Alexander returned a polite refusal, pleading the princess's youth and the objection of the dowager empress to the marriage.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon's answer was to refuse to ratify the 4 January convention, and to announce his engagement to the Archduchess Marie Louise in such a way as to lead Alexander to suppose that the two marriage treaties had been negotiated simultaneously.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] From this time on, the relationship between the two emperors gradually became more and more strained.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Another personal grievance for Alexander towards Napoleon was the annexation of Oldenburg by France in December 1810, as Wilhelm, Duke of Oldenburg (3 January 1754 – 2 July 1823) was the uncle of the tsar.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Furthermore, the disastrous impact of the Continental System on Russian trade made it impossible for the emperor to maintain a policy that was Napoleon's chief motive for the alliance.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander kept Russia as neutral as possible in the ongoing French war with Britain, Russia's own war with Britain barely any more than nominal.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He allowed trade to continue secretly with Britain and did not enforce the blockade required by the Continental System.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1810, he withdrew Russia from the Continental System and trade between Britain and Russia grew.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Relations between France and Russia worsened progressively after 1810.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] By 1811, it became clear that Napoleon was not adhering to his side of the terms of the Treaty of Tilsit.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He had promised assistance to Russia in its war against the Ottoman Empire, but as the campaign went on, France offered no support at all.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] With war imminent between France and Russia, Alexander started to prepare the ground diplomatically.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In April 1812, Russia and Sweden signed a treaty for mutual defence.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A month later, Alexander secured his southern flank through the Treaty of Bucharest (1812), which ended the war against the Ottomans formally.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His diplomats managed to extract promises from Prussia and Austria that should Napoleon invade Russia, the former would help Napoleon as little as possible and that the latter would give no aid at all.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The minister of war, Michael Andreas Barclay de Tolly, had managed the reform and improvement of the Imperial Russian Army before the start of the 1812 campaign.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Primarily on the advice of his sister and Count Aleksey Arakcheyev, Alexander did not take operational control as he had done during the 1805 campaign, instead delegating control to his generals, Barclay de Tolly, Prince Pyotr Bagration and Mikhail Kutuzov.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Despite brief hostilities in the Persian Expedition of 1796, eight years of peace passed before a new conflict erupted between the two empires.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1801, Alexander appointed Pavel Tsitsianov, a die-hard Russian imperialist of Georgian origin, as Russian commander in chief of the Caucasus.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Between 1802 and 1804 he proceeded to impose Russian rule on Western Georgia and some of the Persian controlled khanates around Georgia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Some of these khanates submitted without a fight, but the Ganja Khanate resisted, prompting an attack.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Ganja was ruthlessly sacked during the Siege of Ganja, with some 3,000 – 7,000 inhabitants of Ganja executed, and thousands more expelled to Persia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] These attacks by Tsitsianov formed another casus belli.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 23 May 1804, Persia demanded withdrawal from the regions Russia had occupied, comprising what is now Georgia, Dagestan, and parts of Azerbaijan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Russia refused, stormed Ganja, and declared war.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Following an almost ten-year stalemate centred around what is now Dagestan, east Georgia, Azerbaijan, northern Armenia, with neither party being able to gain the clear upper hand, Russia eventually managed to turn the tide.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After a series of successful offensives led by General Pyotr Kotlyarevsky, including a decisive victory in the Siege of Lankaran, Persia was forced to sue for peace.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In October 1813, the Treaty of Gulistan, negotiated with British mediation and signed at Gulistan, made the Persian Shah Fath Ali Shah cede all Persian territories in the North Caucasus and most of its territories in the South Caucasus to Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] This included what is now Dagestan, Georgia, and most of Azerbaijan.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the summer of 1812 Napoleon invaded Russia.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It was the occupation of Moscow and the desecration of the Kremlin, considered to be the sacred centre of Holy Russia, that changed Alexander's sentiment for Napoleon into passionate hatred.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The campaign of 1812 was the turning point for Alexander's life; after the burning of Moscow, he declared that his own soul had found illumination, and that he had realized once and for all the divine revelation to him of his mission as the peacemaker of Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] While the Russian army retreated deep into Russia for almost three months, the nobility pressured Alexander to relieve the commander of the Russian army, Field Marshal Barclay de Tolly.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander complied and appointed Prince Mikhail Kutuzov to take over command of the army.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 7 September, the Grande Armée faced the Russian army at a small village called Borodino, 110 kilometres (70 mi) west of Moscow.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The battle that followed was the largest and bloodiest single-day action of the Napoleonic Wars, involving more than 250,000 soldiers and resulting in 70,000 casualties.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The outcome of the battle was inconclusive.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Russian army, undefeated in spite of heavy losses, was able to withdraw the following day, leaving the French without the decisive victory Napoleon sought.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A week later, Napoleon entered Moscow, but there was no delegation to meet the Emperor.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Russians had evacuated the city, and the city's governor, Count Fyodor Rostopchin, ordered several strategic points in Moscow to be set ablaze.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The loss of Moscow did not compel Alexander to sue for peace.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After staying in the city for a month, Napoleon moved his army out southwest toward Kaluga, where Kutuzov was encamped with the Russian army.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The French advance toward Kaluga was checked by the Russian army, and Napoleon was forced to retreat to the areas already devastated by the invasion.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the weeks that followed the *Grande Armée* starved and suffered from the onset of the Russian Winter.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Lack of food and fodder for the horses and persistent attacks upon isolated troops from Russian peasants and Cossacks led to great losses.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] When the remnants of the French army eventually crossed the Berezina river in November, only 27,000 soldiers remained; the *Grande Armée* had lost some 380,000 men dead and 100,000 captured.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Following the crossing of the Berezina, Napoleon left the army and returned to Paris to protect his position as Emperor and to raise more forces to resist the advancing Russians.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The campaign ended on 14 December 1812, with the last French troops finally leaving Russian soil.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The campaign was a turning point in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon's reputation was severely shaken, and French hegemony in Europe was weakened.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The *Grande Armée*, made up of French and allied forces, was reduced to a fraction of its initial strength.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] These events triggered a major shift in European politics.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] France's ally Prussia, soon followed by Austria, broke their imposed alliance with Napoleon and switched sides, triggering the War of the Sixth Coalition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] With the Russian army following up victory over Napoleon in 1812, the Sixth Coalition was formed with Russia, Prussia, Great Britain, Sweden, Spain, and other nations.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Although the French were victorious in the initial battles during the campaign in Germany, the entry of Austria into the war led to France's decisive defeat at the Battle of Leipzig in the autumn of 1813, which proved to be a massive victory for the Coalition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Following the battle, the Pro-French Confederation of the Rhine collapsed, thereby ending Napoleon's hold on territory east of the Rhine forever.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander, being the supreme commander of the Coalition forces in the theatre and the paramount monarch among the three main Coalition monarchs, ordered all Coalition forces in Germany to cross the Rhine and invade France.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Coalition forces, divided into three groups, entered northeastern France in January 1814.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Facing them in the theatre were the French forces numbering only about 70,000 men.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In spite of being heavily outnumbered, Napoleon defeated the divided Coalition forces in the battles at Brienne and La Rothière, but could not stop the Coalition's advance and triumphant victory over Napoleon.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Austrian Emperor Francis I and King Frederick William III of Prussia felt demoralized upon hearing about Napoleon's victories since the start of the campaign.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] They even considered ordering a general retreat.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] But Alexander was far more determined than ever to victoriously enter Paris whatever the cost, imposing his will upon Karl Philipp, Prince of Schwarzenberg, and the wavering monarchs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 28 March, Coalition forces advanced towards Paris and prepared to launch an assault.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Camping outside the city on 29 March, the Coalition armies were to assault the city from its northern and eastern sides the next morning on 30 March.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The battle started that same morning with intense artillery bombardment from the Coalition positions.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Early in the morning the Coalition attack began when the Russians attacked and drove back the French skirmishers near Belleville before being driven back themselves by French cavalry from the city's eastern suburbs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] By 7:00 a.m. the Russians attacked the Young Guard near Romainville in the centre of the French lines and after some time and hard fighting, pushed them back.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A few hours later the Prussians, under Gebhard Leberecht von Blücher, attacked north of the city and carried the French position around Aubervilliers, but did not press their attack.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Württemberg troops seized the positions at Saint-Maur to the southeast, with Austrian troops in support.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The Russian forces then assailed the heights of Montmartre in the city's northeast.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Control of the heights was severely contested, until the French forces surrendered.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander sent an envoy to meet with the French to hasten the surrender.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He offered generous terms to the French and although having intended to avenge Moscow, he declared himself to be bringing peace to France rather than its destruction.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 31 March Talleyrand gave the key of the city to the tsar.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Later that day the Coalition armies triumphantly entered the city with Alexander at the head of the army followed by the King of Prussia and Prince Schwarzenberg.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Until this battle it had been nearly 400 years since a foreign army had entered Paris, during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 2 April, the Sénat conservateur passed the *Acte de déchéance de l'Empereur*, which declared Napoleon deposed.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Napoleon was in Fontainebleau when he heard that Paris had surrendered.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Outraged, he wanted to march on the capital, but his marshals refused to fight for him and repeatedly urged him to surrender.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He abdicated in favour of his son on 4 April, but the Allies rejected this out of hand, forcing Napoleon to abdicate unconditionally on 6 April.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The terms of his abdication, which included his exile to the Isle of Elba, were settled in the Treaty of Fontainebleau on 11 April.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A reluctant Napoleon ratified it two days later, marking the end of the War of the Sixth Coalition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander tried to calm the unrest of his conscience by correspondence with the leaders of the evangelical revival on the continent and sought for omens and supernatural guidance in texts and passages of scripture.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It was not, however, according to his own account, until he met the Baroness de Krüdener—a religious adventuress who made the conversion of princes her special mission—at Basel, in the autumn of 1813, that his soul found peace.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] From this time a mystic pietism became the avowed force of his political, as of his private actions.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Madame de Krüdener, and her colleague, the evangelist Henri-Louis Empaytaz, became the confidants of the emperor's most secret thoughts; and during the campaign that ended in the occupation of Paris the imperial prayer-meetings were the oracle on whose revelations hung the fate of the world.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Such was Alexander's mood when the downfall of Napoleon left him one of the most powerful sovereigns in Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] With the memory of the Treaty of Tilsit still fresh in men's minds, it was not unnatural that to cynical men of the world like Klemens Wenzel von Metternich he merely seemed to be disguising "under the language of evangelical abnegation" vast and perilous schemes of ambition.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The puzzled powers were, in fact, the more inclined to be suspicious in view of other, and seemingly inconsistent, tendencies of the emperor, which yet seemed all to point to a like disquieting conclusion.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] For Madame de Krüdener was not the only influence behind the throne; and, though Alexander had declared war against the Revolution, La Harpe (his erstwhile tutor) was once more at his elbow, and the catchwords of the gospel of humanity were still on his lips.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The very proclamations which denounced Napoleon as "the genius of evil", denounced him in the name of "liberty", and of "enlightenment".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Conservatives suspected Alexander of a monstrous intrigue by which the eastern autocrat would ally with the Jacobinism of all Europe, aiming at an all-powerful Russia in place of an all-powerful France.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] At the Congress of Vienna Alexander's attitude accentuated this distrust.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh, whose single-minded aim was the restoration of "a just equilibrium" in Europe, reproached the Tsar to his face for a "conscience" which led him to imperil the concert of the powers by keeping his hold on Poland in violation of his treaty obligation.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] During the Congress of Vienna at Easter 1815, Tsar Alexander I of Russia expressed a desire to “visit a Slavic church,” and Emperor Francis I of Austria took him to a service at the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church of St.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Barbara in Vienna, whose parish priest at that time was the prominent Ukrainian religious, cultural, and political figure Ivan Snihurskyi (later Bishop of Peremyshl).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Once a supporter of limited liberalism, as seen in his approval of the representative institutions in the Ionian Islands, Grand Duchy of Finland and the Constitution of the Kingdom of Poland in 1815, from the end of the year 1818 Alexander's views began to change.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A revolutionary conspiracy among the officers of the Russian Imperial Guard, and a plot to kidnap him on his way to the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle, are said to have shaken his liberal beliefs.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] At Aix he came for the first time into intimate contact with Metternich.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] From this time dates the ascendancy of Metternich over the mind of the Russian Emperor and in the councils of Europe.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] It was, however, no case of sudden conversion.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander deprecated any intervention of a European league in the affairs of individucal nations to support "the absurd pretensions of "absolute power".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He still declared his belief in free institutions with limitations.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] "Liberty", he maintained, "should be confined within just limits.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] And the limits of liberty are the principles of order".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander's conversion was completed by the 1820 revolutions in Naples and Piedmont, combined with increasingly disquieting symptoms of discontent in France, Germany, and among his own people.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the seclusion of the little town of Troppau, where in October 1820 the powers met in conference, Metternich cemented his influence over Alexander, which had been wanting amid the turmoil and intrigues of Vienna and Aix.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] During a friendly conversation over afternoon tea, the disillusioned autocrat confessed his mistake.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] "You have nothing to regret," he said sadly to the exultant chancellor, "but I have!".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In January, Alexander had still upheld the ideal of a free confederation of the European states, the Holy Alliance, against the policy of a dictatorship of the great powers, the Quadruple Treaty.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He gave in on 19 November by signing the Troppau Protocol, which consecrated the claims of collective Europe to interfere in the internal concerns of the sovereign states.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] At the Congress of Laibach, which had been adjourned in the spring of 1821, Alexander received news of the Greek revolt against the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] From this time until his death, Alexander's mind was torn between his dreams of a stable confederation of Europe and his traditional mission as leader of the Orthodox crusade against the Ottomans.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] At first, under the careful advice of Metternich, Alexander chose the former.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He made some effort to reconcile his loyalties.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Metternich opposed this, putting the Austrian-led balance of power (including the Ottoman Empire) above the interests of Christendom.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] This opened Alexander's eyes to the Austria's true attitude towards his ideals.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Back in Russia, far from the fascination of Metternich's personality, he was once again moved by the aspirations of his people, and Russian policy swung toward the Greek cause.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1823 the 1817–1824 cholera pandemic reached Astrakhan, and the Tsar ordered an anti-cholera campaign that was imitated in other countries.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] On 9 October 1793, Alexander married Louise of Baden, known as Elizabeth Alexeievna after her conversion to the Orthodox Church.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He later told his friend Frederick William III that the marriage, a political match devised by his grandmother, Catherine the Great, regrettably proved to be a misfortune for him and his spouse.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Their two children died young, though their common sorrow drew the spouses closer together.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] After a relationship with his mistress Maria Naryshkina from 1799 until 1818, Alexander suffered the death of their beloved daughter Sophia Naryshkina, and the Empress' generous sympathy for his grief strengthened their marital bond.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In 1809, he was widely rumoured to have had an affair with the Finnish noblewoman Ulla Möllersvärd and to have had a child by her, but this is not confirmed.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] With his mind deteriorating, Alexander grew increasingly suspicious, withdrawn, religious, and less active.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Some historians conclude that his profile "coincides precisely with the schizophrenic prototype: a withdrawn, seclusive, rather shy, introvertive, unaggressive, and somewhat apathetic individual".
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In the autumn of 1825 the Emperor undertook a voyage to the south of Russia due to the increasing illness of his wife.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] During his trip he himself caught typhus, from which he died in the southern city of Taganrog on 19 November 1825 (Old Style).
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] However, news of his death did not reach the capital until December.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His two brothers disputed who would become tsar—each wanted the other to do so.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] His wife died a few months later as the emperor's body was transported to Saint Petersburg for the funeral.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] He was interred at the Saints Peter and Paul Cathedral of the Peter and Paul Fortress in Saint Petersburg on 13 March 1826.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] A popular legend has it that Tsar Alexander faked his death and lived as a hermit under the name Feodor Kuzmich, a theory often resurrected by popular writers.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The theory involves the curious similarities between Alexander and Kuzmich.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Svetlana Semyonova, president of the Russian Graphological Society, judged Alexander's and Kuzmich's handwriting to be identical.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] The priest attending Feodor Kuzmich on his deathbed reportedly asked him if he was, in fact, Alexander the Blessed.
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] In response, Kuzmich said, "Your works are wonderful, Lord ...
[src:alexander-i-of-russia/alexander-i-of-russia] Alexander's letters to his grandfather, Frederick II Eugene, Duke of Württemberg, (together with letters from his siblings) written between 1795 and 1797, are preserved in the State Archive of Stuttgart (Hauptstaatsarchiv Stuttgart) in Stuttgart, Germany.
